Create bridge utilities to convert between TC39 Signals (internal reactivity) and Channels (external communication).

Two Bridge Directions:
1. signalToChannel() - Expose signal changes as a Channel
2. channelToSignal() - Subscribe to channel, update signal

API Design:
```typescript
// Signal → Channel (for exposing internal state)
function signalToChannel<T>(sig: Signal<T>): Channel<T> {
  return {
    async *[Symbol.asyncIterator]() {
      let prev = sig.get();
      while (true) {
        const current = sig.get();
        if (current !== prev) {
          yield current;
          prev = current;
        }
        await nextFrame(); // Wait for next change
      }
    },
    close() { /* cleanup */ },
    get closed() { return false; },
    get buffered() { return 0; },
  };
}

// Channel → Signal (for consuming external events)
function channelToSignal<T>(
  channel: Channel<T>,
  initial: T
): Signal<T> {
  const sig = signal(initial);
  (async () => {
    for await (const value of channel) {
      sig.set(value);
    }
  })();
  return sig;
}

// DOM Event → Channel (for external browser events)
function domEventChannel<K extends keyof HTMLElementEventMap>(
  element: HTMLElement,
  eventName: K,
  options?: { signal?: AbortSignal }
): Channel<HTMLElementEventMap[K]> {
  // Convert DOM event stream to Channel
}
```

Use Cases:
1. Widget exposes internal signal as port: `port('status') → signalToChannel(this.statusSignal)`
2. Widget subscribes to external channel: `const state = channelToSignal(actor.port('updates'))`
3. Widget bridges DOM events: `port('clicks') → domEventChannel(this, 'click')`

