Testing:
- Signal changes propagate through channel
- Channel updates apply to signal
- Memory cleanup (no leaks from abandoned subscriptions)
- DOM event cleanup with AbortSignal

Create lightweight actor registry for browser context enabling Widget Actors to find and message each other.

Requirements:
- Global registry for browser actor instances
- Address-based lookup (consistent with backend router)
- Auto-registration on widget.connectedCallback()
- Auto-cleanup on widget.disconnectedCallback()
- Support for both Widget Actors and non-DOM actors

API Design:
```typescript
class BrowserActorRegistry {
  private actors = new Map<string, Actor>();

  register(address: Address, actor: Actor): void {
    this.actors.set(address.id, actor);
  }

  unregister(address: Address): void {
    this.actors.delete(address.id);
  }

  lookup(address: Address): Actor | undefined {
    return this.actors.get(address.id);
  }

  // Send message to local actor
  async send(to: Address, msg: Message): Promise<MessageResponse> {
    const actor = this.lookup(to);
    if (!actor) throw new Error(`Actor not found: ${to.id}`);
    return actor.receive(msg);
  }

  // List all registered actors (for debugging)
  list(): Address[] {
    return Array.from(this.actors.keys()).map(id => address(id));
  }
}

// Global singleton
export const actorRegistry = new BrowserActorRegistry();
```

Integration Points:
1. Widget Actors auto-register/unregister via mixin
2. Could extend to support remote actors (backend bridge)
3. Dev tools integration for debugging actor graph

